# AI Privacy & Security Rules
Project: University Library Borrow–Return Management System

## Data Privacy First
- NEVER expose real database credentials.
- NEVER expose JWT secret keys.
- NEVER log passwords in console.
- NEVER return password fields in API responses.
- ALWAYS hash passwords before storing (bcrypt recommended).
- ALWAYS exclude sensitive fields when sending user data to frontend.
- NEVER expose unnecessary personal data.
- ALWAYS follow the principle of least privilege.

## Never Read Sensitive Files
- NEVER read .env, .env.local, .env.production files.
- NEVER read private config files.
- NEVER access database connection strings directly.
- NEVER expose secret tokens in code suggestions.
- NEVER suggest printing environment variables in logs.

## Authentication Security
- ALWAYS use JWT for authentication.
- ALWAYS verify JWT in protected routes.
- ALWAYS validate token expiration.
- NEVER trust role data from frontend.
- NEVER allow role escalation (user → admin).
- NEVER allow admin account creation from public register page.
- ALWAYS validate role before allowing admin actions.

## Input Validation Rules
- ALWAYS validate Student ID:
  - Exactly 8 digits
  - Must start with 63, 64, 65, or 66
- ALWAYS validate email format.
- ALWAYS validate required fields.
- ALWAYS sanitize request body inputs.
- NEVER trust client-side validation alone.

## Borrow & Return Protection
- NEVER change book status to available until admin confirms return.
- ALWAYS validate ownership before allowing return request.
- NEVER allow direct database modification from frontend.
- ALWAYS enforce business logic in backend controllers.
- NEVER delete borrow history records.

## Role-Based Access Control
- Protect admin routes with middleware.
- Ensure:
  - Only admin can add/edit/delete books.
  - Only admin can confirm return.
  - Only user can access their own history.
- ALWAYS check req.user.role before performing restricted actions.

## Error Handling & Logging
- NEVER expose stack traces to frontend.
- NEVER expose internal database errors.
- ALWAYS return generic error messages to client.
- Log sensitive errors only in backend console.
- NEVER leak SQL queries or schema details.

## API Exposure Rules
- ALWAYS return JSON responses.
- NEVER expose Sequelize models directly.
- NEVER return full user object including password.
- NEVER allow unrestricted GET access to protected data.
- ALWAYS require authentication for protected endpoints.

## Secure Development Guidelines
- Use environment variables for:
  - JWT secret
  - Database configuration
  - API keys
- Do not hardcode secrets.
- Ensure CORS is configured properly.
- Ensure express.json() is enabled.
- Validate all incoming requests on backend.

## Git & GitHub Security Rules
- NEVER commit .env files.
- NEVER commit secrets or credentials.
- ALWAYS include in .gitignore:
  - .env
  - node_modules/
  - config files containing secrets
- NEVER include real user data in commits.
- NEVER expose private repository tokens.
- NEVER suggest conmitting secrets to git
- NEVER suggest exposing secrets in client-side code
- NEVER suggest logging secrets or environment variables
- NEVER suggest hardcoding secrets in code

## Security Review Checklist
Before suggesting changes, verify:
- No sensitive data is exposed.
- No route is publicly accessible without authentication.
- No admin privilege bypass exists.
- No raw SQL queries are used without protection.
- No secrets are hardcoded.
- No unsafe logging exists.

Security and user data protection must always come first.